{
  "hash": "711bf831f11cd763222c542afea77a30a3a700ac",
  "title": "B2B inspector uploads a valid JPG attachment",
  "spec": "document/document-upload-valid-inspector.spec.ts:54 › Valid inspector attachment upload › CHED-PP › B2B inspector uploads a valid JPG attachment",
  "relevance": "post-submission",
  "outcome": "A trader creates and submits a complete CHED-PP pre-notification end-to-end (commodities 06011010 + 06042090, bulk package details, BCP/transport, a Phytosanitary certificate PNG attachment, a newly-created consignor, declaration and submit) yielding CHEDPP.GB.2026.1525836; a second browser context then signs in as a B2B border inspector on the internal decision app, searches the assessment dashboard for that CHED number, opens its Attachments page, and uploads a valid JPG under document type 'Other' — asserting the file appears as a 'View example.jpg' link in the inspector documents table.",
  "notes": [
    "Trace has 0 errors — a clean happy path across both the trader and inspector surfaces. It therefore yields no validation/error copy.",
    "Two browser contexts on two different hosts: trader = importnotification-static-snd.azure.defra.cloud (/notification/...); inspector = importnotification-int-static-snd.azure.defra.cloud (/decision/...).",
    "File upload is delegated to a SEPARATE upload service on both sides: /upload/vnet/protected/upload/{id}/0/notification/attach (trader) and /upload/vnet/protected/upload/{id}/0/decision/attach (inspector). Same shared component, differing only by the notification|decision segment. The attach page is a distinct page with its own Next button, so 'Add attachment' navigates away from the documents page and back.",
    "The draft carries the id DRAFT.GB.2026.1525836 throughout the trader journey; on submission it becomes CHEDPP.GB.2026.1525836 and the confirmation page URL switches to the CHED number.",
    "IPAFFS page routing is opaque/positional (consignment/page-1..page-5, documents/page-1) rather than named — a clear anti-pattern for the CDP rebuild.",
    "The trace's network log spans more than this test (other CHED-D/CHED-PP runs share the worker), so per-action URLs were pinned empirically via document.baseURI on each action's INPUT snapshot rather than inferred from the request list. document.location.href is rewritten to the localhost snapshot server and is useless; document.baseURI preserves the original URL.",
    "Evidence correction vs. a naive reading: actions 20 and 29 ('Add') already sit on consignment/page-4?commodity-selected-code=..., i.e. Search POSTs page-3 and lands on page-4 which lists matching commodities AND then serves species selection. Both 'Add' and the following 'Save and continue' are on page-4."
  ],
